<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp In the 30th century, man has moved off earth and out of its home solar system to a new one, one that is not dead.  The new solar system that man inhabits is called Bria after the 27th century scientist Martha Bria that found the new system that was capable of human habitation.  In this new system there is 2 planets capable of supporting human life:  Agis, and Felkos.  On Agis the human race did all the things right that they did wrong on earth.  Pollution is not a problem because of the discovery of the Kiskov engine.  This new engine transmutes carbon dioxide into energy (actually it forces the oxygen and carbon atoms into each other separating them in and giving off much energy).  The downside to this is that matter is used up and that it gives off much heat.  Agis is a bustling metropolis filled with many gigantic cities.  Overpopulation is not a problem because all families are only allowed to have 2 children, although some very rich families have found ways around this.  As you might have guessed there is allot of treachery and the whole government is full of evil and determined to only have a perfect race and world.  The planet of Felkos was humanities first try at new population of a planet.  When humanity first started to poor onto the planet new cities were being made and once they were all up and ready for habitation they turned on the new Kiskov engines.  However there was a bad chemical reaction and gigantic holes were formed in the planet turning into a deformed mass, also throwing its gravity into an unpredictable twirl around the sun in a sort of oval shape.  Felkos has many deserted cities on it, and in the explosions, the atmosphere was also blown to pieces so the planet is not livable on without support.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp On Agis there is a group of rich evil Business men with a dark passion for a sort of twisted war game much like the Gladiators of Rome.  The game consists of gigantic humanoid machines called Cidals that are very ornate and include various weapons that are used on other Cidals.  These machines run on Kiskov engines so they are very powerful and produce immense heat making them impossible to be used on a populated planet.  This game often referred to as Gladiator Fights, or CB Games takes place on the deserted planet of Felkos where the unpredictable gravity makes for a fun match.  These battles get very serious and have much evil plots involved.  So evil are these that sometimes a Cidal will be equipped with a self-destruct mechanism just so the opponent is not left alive.  As you also may have guessed there is much money involved in these CB Games and betting is a key part in the fights, so much that more money is made in betting than in Prize money, and Cidals are very expensive to maintain.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The evil syndicates and businesses of Agis are not the only things to worry about.  Just before global warming overtook the entire planet a computer was left running with a special program on it.  This program was one that gave the computer a willing to survive, reproduce and prosper.  Over the centuries that humans have been gone from the now uninhabitable Earth the computers have developed intelligence and machines to take over other planets and have already taken over the entire system that Earth was in.  The humans from Agis have found out about these intelligent machines at the same time that the machines found out about the humans.  The thing that was actually sent out to earth was a group of Cidals that were to have a fight on the Earth; it was to be the CB game of the century!  Therefore, the first thing the computers saw was these Cidals and the best thing to fight one of these mammoth humanoid machines would be more Cidals, so the machines created there own Cidals and they swarmed the human vehicles and destroyed every one.  The whole of Agis was sent into deep shock.  They now had an enemy they were not even sure that they could compete with; there only hope was to make something to battle these insane Cidal toting machines.<br>
